@node "intro" "Introduction"



   @{b}Backclock@{ub}
       Something missed on my Workbench:

       A <transparent> clock which opens on the Workbench and very is easy to use.
  So, I started to search on aminet but nothing suits what I was searching for
  then I decided to code it myself .


       This is an analogic (and digital too) clock that works on the screen you
     choose.

       There is no border in the window, and you can choose the needles color.



@endnode

@node "requi" "Requirements"



  In order to run this prog you need:

    - An Amiga with at least a 68020
    - OS 3.0, 3.1 or better prefered
    - math libraries
    - notifyintuition.library V2.0+                       (get it in fastiprefs.lha)
    - rtracker.library V10                                  (present in the package)
    - popupmenu.library V6, only for the clock designer     (present in the package)
    - quickhelp.library V37, only for BackclockPrefs        (present in the package)
    - led.image if you want to have leds                    (present in the package)

  Tested succesfully:

   V3.22
    * Amiga 1200 Escom + Blizzard 1260/60 MHz / 48Mo, kit SCSI Phase-5

   V3.21
    * Amiga 4000T WB3.1 + 18 MB RAM

   V3.1
    * Amiga 1200 Escom + Blizzard 1260/66 MHz / 32Mo

   V3.0
    * Amiga 1200 Escom

    * Amiga 1200 Escom + Blizzard 1260/50 MHz / 32Mo

    * Amiga 1200 Escom + Blizzard 1260/66 MHz / 32Mo

    * Amiga 4000 OS3.1, Picasso II with Picasso96

    * Amiga 4000T WB 3.1, 18 MB RAM

    * Amiga 1200T OS3.1 68040/40Mhz, 64MB, Picasso II with P96

  V2.2

    * Amiga 4000, 64MB, OS3.1, setpatch 43.6, P96

    * Amiga 1400T + Blizzard 68030/50 MHz WB 3.1 2M chip 16M fast

    * Amiga 1200 68040/25 MHz, 160 MHz Blizzard PPC

    * Amiga 2000 68030, OS3.1, PicassoII with Picasso96, 24meg RAM

  V2.1

    * UAE Cyrix PR-300, W95, 64Mo, Picasso96

@endnode

@node "insta" "Installation"




    To install simply run the provided Installer script

      You need to install the notifyintuition.library into your libs: dir


        * sources are given too but if you want to recompile it
          contact me first to obtain files for using rtracker.library




@endnode

@node "custo" "Customizing"

  In this version of backclock (version 3.1 +), a new program appeared:

  The clock designer.


  @{u} What is this ?@{uu}
  This software allows you to draw your own arrow shape

  @{u} Requirements @{uu}
  You need popupmenu.library version 6

  @{u} How to use it ?@{uu}
  Very simple:
  It is like a DPaint or PPaint, simple press left button to add a point
  (to make lines).
  The right button allows you to delete a point (remove) or
  Change the last selected point in order to insert points in the line
  (make this point be active). This point goes white.

  Draw the arrow as if it was 12 o'clock, ex:

                  |
                  |
                 _|_
                | . |
                |___|

  The blue point shows where the point of rotation is.


  Button Save: select the type of arrow either second, minute or hours.
  (nb: this will overwrite the file backclock.(s|m|h) in env: AND envarc:

  Button Clear: to remove all points.

@endnode
@node "usage" "Usage"


  You can start this program by the CLI ou by the Workbench

    Generalities: Backclock is a commodity, it can be stopped with
     exchange (or whatever clone)
     (nb: active/inactive has no effects at all)

     There are 2 gadgets (invisibles): for moving and resizing Backclock.
      There are placed where they would be if they were visibles.

  The following tooltypes/arguments are used:
    @{b}Tooltypes & arguments :@{ub}
      CX_POPPREFS : defines the hotkey which allows to start the prefs program
                    (default: control b)
      CX_PRIORITY : priority of the hotkey (default 0)

    @{b}only Tooltypes@{ub}:
      INITIALWAIT : When starting Backclock, sometimes the background image
                    of the workbench is not displayed immediatly. This tooltype
                    allows you to set the time that Backclock will wait,
                    in order to let the the Workbench displays the background
                    picture.

    @{u}BackclockPrefs@{uu}

      At start, the preferences tool finds the version of Backclock. If you are
      using an old version of Backclock, gadgets that are not handled by Backclock
      are ghosted. In this case, you should reinstall the right version of
      Backclock & BackclockPrefs.

      New, since version 2.45, there is an interactive help system:
      Move your pointer above a gadget and a short description is displayed.
      (nb: this can be stopped, select -help- menu).

    @{b}Explanation of the gadgets@{ub}:
      The colors list : this is the list of all the elements of Backclock
                        that can be modified:
           Seconds    : color of the second hand
           Minutes    :    "     "   minute hand
           Hours      :    "     "   hour hand
           Tics       : color of the graduation
           Background : color of the back (if not transparent)
           Point      : color of the middle point
           Led Back.  : color of inactive LEDs
           Led Fore.  : color of active LEDs

           The colors can be changed thanks to the 3 sliders, on the right
           of the list.

      The checkBoxes : They change the appearance of Backclock

           Fill background: transparent or not if selected
           Fill needles   : Arrows are filled
           Draw seconds   : Draws the seconds
           Draw shadows   : Draws the shadows
           Draw middle point : Draws the middle point
           Display LEDs   : Display the LEDs

      The 2 sliders -shadows-: They change the position of the shadow
           Y offset : move the shadow vertically
           X offset : move the shadow horizontally

      The public screen string: Enter here the name of the public screen
                                where backclock opens. (ex: Workbench)

           If you let this blank, Backclock will always open on the
           frontmost screen.

      The 3 gadgets: Save, use or cancel the modifications

      The menus:
        About : The about-box
        Help  : active or not the help
        Quit  : ...

        Presets : Allows to change the preset
                  (nb: these are installed in
                       SYS:Prefs/presets/Backclock/xxxx where xxxx
                       is the name of the preset)




 

@endnode

@node "bugs" "Sorry, there are some bugs"

  Sends bug reports please...

  * Once the boot is finished, it happens that some windows open and then backclock
    starts and opens its window under the one already present:
    Backclock will copy parts of this window. This is not really a bug, because
    it copies the part of the Workbench where the backclock window will open
    (to make the window transparent!). Just click in the backclock window to
    redraw it with the right content

@endnode

